        "text": "*[Bug 19008] New: on.exit() at top level is a silent no-op*\n<https:\/\/bugs.r-project.org\/show_bug.cgi?id=19008>\n\n            Bug ID: 19008\n           Summary: on.exit() at top level is a silent no-op\n           Product: R\n           Version: R-devel (trunk)\n          Hardware: Other\n                OS: Other\n            Status: UNCONFIRMED\n          Severity: normal\n          Priority: P5\n         Component: Low-level\n          Assignee: <mailto:R-core@R-project.org|R-core@R-project.org>\n          Reporter: <mailto:kevinushey@gmail.com|kevinushey@gmail.com>\n\nFor example, consider the script:\n\n```\non.exit(print(\"exit\"))\n```\n\nThis exit handler will not be executed if at the top-level; e.g. if executed\nvia something like `R -f script.R`. However, it will be executed if run via\n`source(\"script.R\")`.\n\nIs this intentional? If so, I think it's worth documenting this caveat more\nexplicitly in `?on.exit`. Strictly speaking, I believe it behaves as\ndocumented, since in the `Rscript -f script.R` example there indeed is no\nparent function context for `on.exit()` to attach to, but that is likely only\napparent to R experts.\n\nIf not, it would be helpful if these handlers could be registered and executed\non process exit at some appropriate point.\n\nFor posterity, I bumped into this with code of the form:\n\n```\nconn &lt;- socketConnection(...)\non.exit(close(conn))\n```",
